WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:19.769 --> 00:21.563
[whirring]

00:26.234 --> 00:27.569
[David Chang yells]

00:32.490 --> 00:33.783
[whirring stops]

00:33.867 --> 00:37.954
Holy fuck! That was epic fail.

00:43.126 --> 00:45.795
[Chang] American barbecue
is distinctly American.

00:45.879 --> 00:48.089
I'm really interested in how
the rest of the world barbecues.

00:48.673 --> 00:51.050
I see a lot of similarities
in all the cultures.

00:52.302 --> 00:56.639
What if I just cooked Korean barbecue
like an American barbecue place?

01:05.190 --> 01:07.108
[narrator] Junior, he's always hungry.

01:08.234 --> 01:11.446
The pop and sizzle of the juicy meat
seems to say,

01:11.529 --> 01:13.823
"Come and get me. I'm done to a turn."

01:23.875 --> 01:27.086
Our barbecue is prepared
with just the right amount of heat

01:27.170 --> 01:30.882
to keep in the natural juices
and hold in that wonderful flavor.

01:31.591 --> 01:33.218
[TV host speaking Korean]

01:35.720 --> 01:36.638
[advertiser in English] Getting hungry?

01:38.431 --> 01:41.226
Well, we wouldn't just tell you
about Smithfield Barbeque.

01:41.309 --> 01:44.896
Step up and enjoy one
at our refreshment stand right now.

01:49.776 --> 01:52.737
...so that today,
happy folks in every land

01:52.821 --> 01:54.531
are enjoying that old Virginia dish.

02:05.125 --> 02:07.001
Yahoo!

02:08.127 --> 02:11.589
[advertiser] This is the first step
in the disassembly of the pork side.

02:15.510 --> 02:17.137
[Hank Hill] These are medium-rare.

02:17.220 --> 02:20.056
[Bobby Hill] What if somebody
wants theirs well done?

02:20.140 --> 02:22.851
We ask them politely, yet firmly,
to leave.

02:23.726 --> 02:27.230
[advertiser] When you bite into that
luscious Smithfield Barbeque sandwich,

02:27.313 --> 02:30.066
you will find out for yourself
why Kings...

02:30.150 --> 02:32.110
[advertisement continues, distorted]

02:39.534 --> 02:41.411
[thunder rumbling]

02:59.971 --> 03:02.807
[Lang] I started in fine dining
French cuisine,

03:02.891 --> 03:07.562
because there was just some
mystical quality that drew me in.

03:09.147 --> 03:11.733
You can find the same things in barbecue.

03:12.734 --> 03:16.988
Log by log.
Ten, twelve, fifteen hours sometimes.

03:17.071 --> 03:19.490
I mean, you get that same engagement,

03:20.033 --> 03:23.369
because it's about heart
that's in the chef that's cooking it.

03:27.457 --> 03:30.168
Cooking with fire,
it's about connection to me.

03:33.755 --> 03:35.006
All right, let's eat.

03:36.257 --> 03:37.258
[Amelia Gray] Oh, yeah.

03:37.342 --> 03:38.509
[Lang] Beef short ribs.

03:39.802 --> 03:42.639
-Ladies first. [chuckles]
-[Gray] Oh, thank you.

03:43.598 --> 03:44.724
Oh, wow.

03:46.351 --> 03:47.852
I told you last time,

03:47.936 --> 03:50.980
you should just open up a restaurant
where this is like sushi.

03:51.064 --> 03:51.940
Exactly, right?

03:52.023 --> 03:53.983
[Peter Meehan] It could just be one table
at a casino like this,

03:54.067 --> 03:55.944
where you just deal out slices of beef.

03:56.027 --> 03:57.612
-[Gray] It's beautiful.
-[Lang] Taste that.

03:57.695 --> 03:59.864
-That's gold, right there.
-[Gray] Mmm.

04:01.157 --> 04:03.493
-All right, fine. I'll taste it.
-[Gray laughs]

04:04.035 --> 04:05.078
Mmm.

04:06.913 --> 04:09.958
-Awesome.
-There's really nothing quite like this.

04:10.041 --> 04:14.587
I would pay as much money
as I pay in the top sushi restaurants

04:14.671 --> 04:19.801
to just sit down, have a nice glass
of wine or a cold beer, this...

04:19.884 --> 04:24.013
Like, why does a steak house
have to be what it is?

04:26.641 --> 04:29.435
[Meehan] A decade ago,
you were pushing crazy boundaries.

04:29.519 --> 04:31.938
I mean, I remember one time
coming to Daisy May's,

04:32.021 --> 04:36.192
and there was a baby goat covered in,
like, dried cherries on the table.

04:36.276 --> 04:37.110
I remember cooking that.

04:37.193 --> 04:41.197
Those were amazing meals. It seems like
your barbecue has changed over time.

04:41.281 --> 04:44.409
I think that traditional barbecue
is freaking unbelievable,

04:44.492 --> 04:45.994
and I don't wanna change that.

04:46.077 --> 04:49.998
But, for me, I don't look at it
as barbecue when I'm cooking it.

04:50.081 --> 04:52.667
I really look at it
as just live-fire cooking.

04:52.750 --> 04:58.339
Beef and pork with fire
create a super flavor.

04:58.423 --> 05:04.095
You tap into something really fundamental,
I think, about humans.

05:04.178 --> 05:07.473
What advice do you give to people
who are trying to get into barbecue?

05:07.557 --> 05:09.058
Just watch the smoke.

05:16.941 --> 05:20.737
[Meehan] I've been working on
a barbecue book for, like, a yearish now

05:20.820 --> 05:23.072
and done a lot of cooking myself.

05:23.781 --> 05:25.992
When I was writing for the Times,

05:26.075 --> 05:30.371
it was during the first blossoming
of barbecue in New York City.

05:31.122 --> 05:34.751
So that was when I got to be more critical
about it and started writing about it.

05:35.293 --> 05:38.796
And then recently, it's just become
what we do during the summer.

05:38.880 --> 05:40.548
Cook food for everybody

05:40.631 --> 05:43.801
where I go to spend time on the weekends
outside of the city.

05:45.887 --> 05:48.931
If you're from a place that doesn't
have a deep barbecue tradition,

05:49.015 --> 05:51.601
your entry into what barbecue is

05:51.684 --> 05:55.855
is gonna be this kind of carnival
barker-style battle between places.

06:03.488 --> 06:05.073
[indistinct chatter]

06:07.575 --> 06:12.080
[Meehan] We're at a very American event.
We are in the middle of America doing it.

06:12.163 --> 06:15.541
And, I mean,
it's gruesome or it's beautiful.

06:15.625 --> 06:18.002
I guess that depends on
your perspective on things.

06:18.086 --> 06:20.755
♪ Hot barbeque today! ♪

06:22.757 --> 06:25.510
[Mike Mills] You got about
five different styles of cooking.

06:26.260 --> 06:30.515
And what we try to do here
is to mimic those styles of cooking.

06:30.598 --> 06:34.102
Because the guys that are coming here
to cook, they're pitmasters.

06:34.185 --> 06:35.603
They have their style down.

06:35.686 --> 06:38.147
♪ Hot barbecue! ♪

06:38.231 --> 06:40.566
[Meehan] What is the definition
of North Carolina barbecue,

06:40.650 --> 06:41.818
at least for you?

06:41.901 --> 06:44.403
[Elliot Moss] A lot of times,
Carolina style is what I call it.

06:44.487 --> 06:47.490
It's whole hog, vinegar, pepper,
and cooked over wood and chopped.

06:47.573 --> 06:49.826
Hopefully, it's some good, happy pigs.

06:49.909 --> 06:52.370
[Pat Martin] The one thing I love
about Carolina barbecue

06:52.453 --> 06:54.789
is they put the skins in there with it.

06:54.872 --> 06:55.915
I've thought about doing it,

06:55.998 --> 06:57.542
but then I would be
getting out of my lane.

06:57.625 --> 07:01.629
I liken it to the cheese in France.
You drive 50 miles, it changes.

07:01.712 --> 07:02.922
♪ Hot barbeque! ♪

07:03.005 --> 07:06.759
In Nashville, we cook really low,
and we cook for 24 hours.

07:06.843 --> 07:09.220
We don't want the skin to get brittle,

07:09.303 --> 07:12.390
because we need that skin
to hold all that rendered fat,

07:12.473 --> 07:15.143
to protect the shoulder and belly
while the hams are dragging.

07:15.726 --> 07:17.478
[Meehan]
What kind of barbecue do you cook?

07:17.562 --> 07:22.275
I cook West Tennessee-style barbecue,
and our specialty is dry ribs.

07:23.401 --> 07:25.153
♪ Hot barbeque! ♪

07:25.236 --> 07:29.657
[Carey Bringle] A true dry rib is smoked
with nothing on it except for kosher salt.

07:29.740 --> 07:32.493
And then, we have a barbecue seasoning.

07:32.577 --> 07:35.621
It's not heavy in salt or heavy in sugar
like a rub would be.

07:35.705 --> 07:37.832
You get the full flavor of the pork,

07:37.915 --> 07:40.793
and you get the brightness
of all the spices as a salt substitute.

07:40.877 --> 07:42.670
And that's a true dry rib.

07:43.296 --> 07:45.840
[man] Growing up in Texas,
the first time I had Carolina style,

07:45.923 --> 07:49.802
it was unrecognizable to me
as being barbecue.

07:49.886 --> 07:54.974
My expectation being Texas style were like
whole cuts of meat, like ribs and brisket.

07:55.057 --> 07:58.811
[Bringle] Growing up in Tennessee,
they did not consider beef barbecue.

07:58.895 --> 08:02.940
They'd tell you, "That's not barbecue,
that's a steak." And, "Go to Texas."

08:03.024 --> 08:05.776
[Moss] This is the style
that I grew up on, so I'm cooking it.

08:05.860 --> 08:08.279
I know people are gonna be like,
"This isn't barbecue."

08:08.362 --> 08:11.657
But the little kids that are coming,
I take 'em in

08:11.741 --> 08:13.784
and open the pig cooler,
and they're, like, "Wow!"

08:14.410 --> 08:15.578
They'll never forget that.

08:15.661 --> 08:18.456
Hopefully, they become
lifelong fans of our barbecue.

08:18.539 --> 08:21.334
[Martin]
Barbecue is America's peasant food.

08:21.417 --> 08:23.169
We didn't invent live-fire cooking.

08:23.252 --> 08:25.922
But I think this country is the one
that owned it and said,

08:26.005 --> 08:27.673
"We're gonna try to make this ours."

08:27.757 --> 08:30.092
♪ Hot barbeque! ♪

08:30.176 --> 08:33.846
[Meehan] Regional styles of barbecue
are only, like, 120 years old.

08:34.554 --> 08:37.558
Like, before then,
there weren't barbecue restaurants,

08:37.642 --> 08:39.309
so there wasn't an individual style.

08:39.393 --> 08:42.563
That's what bothers me. It became regional
because someone decided

08:42.647 --> 08:44.649
to take a chance and do something
a little bit differently.

08:44.732 --> 08:46.275
-Yeah.
-[Chang] Right?

08:46.359 --> 08:49.737
And I hate when things
become an institution.

08:49.820 --> 08:50.696
[Lang] That's right.

08:50.780 --> 08:53.324
I think it's a fight
against homogenization.

08:53.407 --> 08:55.535
Rather than saying, "We're better."

08:55.618 --> 08:57.954
-I'm trying to think about it that way.
-[Gray] Mmm-hmm.

08:58.037 --> 08:59.956
I mean, the pitmasters that I've known
and talked to,

09:00.039 --> 09:01.791
they don't say, "This is better."

09:01.874 --> 09:03.501
But they do say, "This is mine."

09:03.584 --> 09:08.464
Would you three consider barbecue
like jazz and baseball?

09:08.548 --> 09:10.341
Something that's uniquely American?

09:10.424 --> 09:12.718
-[Lang] I'm gonna say yes.
-Or New World.

09:12.802 --> 09:14.470
Then what about Peking duck?

09:15.638 --> 09:17.223
How is that not barbecue?

09:17.306 --> 09:18.641
I would call it barbecue.

09:18.724 --> 09:24.647
And then Korean barbecue,
which is its own form of barbecue,

09:24.730 --> 09:25.648
which is not...

09:25.731 --> 09:27.692
-[Lang] Exactly.
-...American barbecue.

09:27.775 --> 09:29.986
Only Americans say, "That's not barbecue."

09:30.069 --> 09:33.656
-[Lang] It's true.
-No one from Beijing is saying...

09:33.739 --> 09:36.200
"That's not Peking duck."

09:36.951 --> 09:38.995
-You know what I mean? [laughs]
-It's true.

09:39.078 --> 09:42.707
It's a very American-centric way
of looking at the world,

09:42.790 --> 09:45.376
and that's a wrong way to do it, actually.

10:01.517 --> 10:02.852
[indistinct chatter]

10:04.437 --> 10:07.440
-Hi. David. Nice to meet you.
-[Jenee Kim] Nice to meet you.

10:07.523 --> 10:09.358
-How're you doing?
-Hi there.

10:09.442 --> 10:10.943
-Where's, uh...
-Up there.

10:11.027 --> 10:14.697
-[Dave Choe] Oh, he's on there?
-[Chang] I'm up there! Oh, my God!

10:14.780 --> 10:17.658
-[Choe] Whoa! Keanu Reeves?
-[Kim] He was here, yeah.

10:17.742 --> 10:20.911
-Psy?
-Psy always comes here, when he's here.

10:20.995 --> 10:22.622
Where are you?
How come you're not on the wall?

10:22.705 --> 10:23.831
Yeah, uh...

10:23.914 --> 10:25.666
[Chang] You took me here.

10:25.750 --> 10:29.462
I've been eating at this fucking
restaurant since it opened, basically.

10:29.545 --> 10:32.423
They have every fucking Korean
on the wall except for me.

10:34.467 --> 10:35.551
[Chang] When did you guys open up?

10:35.635 --> 10:36.802
2003.

10:36.886 --> 10:39.096
You weren't here during the LA Riots.

10:39.180 --> 10:40.014
No.

10:40.097 --> 10:41.891
The street that this restaurant's on,
Vermont...

10:41.974 --> 10:45.895
It was '92, LA riots, it was...
Everything was on fire.

10:45.978 --> 10:51.025
In 2003, was there already white people
starting to eat this kind of food?

10:51.108 --> 10:53.486
There was some shift
that happened at some point.

10:53.569 --> 10:57.031
There's Chinese food, and then
in the '80s, people started eating sushi,

10:57.114 --> 10:58.449
and then there was Japanese food.

10:58.532 --> 11:00.993
But Korean food was still, like,
an unknown thing.

11:01.077 --> 11:02.745
What I've always loved
about your restaurant

11:02.828 --> 11:04.330
is all of your banchan is delicious.

11:04.955 --> 11:07.333
That's what makes Korean barbecue
Korean barbecue.

11:07.416 --> 11:09.710
You have to have all this.

11:09.794 --> 11:12.046
Yeah, a lot of variety of banchans.

11:12.129 --> 11:15.674
That's really Korean tradition, you know?
Like royal cuisine.

11:15.758 --> 11:18.844
The king used to eat
with, like, 12 different kinds of--

11:18.928 --> 11:21.931
That's what I'm trying to tell him.
This is like royal cuisine.

11:22.014 --> 11:24.809
But we eat this shit every day.
So that's why we're fat now.

11:24.892 --> 11:29.230
That kind of eating you would do, like,
once a year on a holiday or something.

11:29.313 --> 11:30.898
-[Chang laughs]
-Sorry, guys.

11:30.981 --> 11:31.941
[speaks Korean]

11:32.024 --> 11:33.651
[in English] Hi, I'm Steve.
Nice to meet you.

11:33.734 --> 11:34.944
What's up?

11:35.694 --> 11:37.947
-[Choe] Are you on the wall?
-[Yeun] No, I'm not on the wall.

11:38.030 --> 11:39.156
He's not on the wall, either.

11:39.240 --> 11:41.617
No, it's okay. I come in here
with a hat on every time.

11:41.700 --> 11:43.244
After me, he's the next famous Korean...

11:43.327 --> 11:44.912
-No, no, no. [laughs]
-...and he's not on the wall.

11:44.995 --> 11:48.374
Do you think this is barbecue,
like when Americans think about barbecue?

11:48.457 --> 11:50.126
Do you think that this is barbecue?

11:50.209 --> 11:52.503
-What Americans think about barbecue?
-Yeah.

11:52.586 --> 11:56.632
Yeah... No. But it's coming.

11:56.715 --> 11:59.427
-It's coming.
-Right? In people's brains.

11:59.510 --> 12:00.928
But did you grow up eating this?

12:01.011 --> 12:02.471
-Oh, yeah.
-See?

12:02.555 --> 12:06.142
Korean barbecue, it's not a surprise to me
that it's the most mainstream.

12:06.225 --> 12:09.103
You ask anyone now, they'll know bulgogi
and they'll know kalbi.

12:09.186 --> 12:10.062
-[Kim] Kalbi.
-Yeah.

12:10.146 --> 12:12.898
Right? But when you get
to real Korean food?

12:12.982 --> 12:14.942
People will never eat that.

12:15.025 --> 12:18.946
But barbecue is the vehicle where
everyone's gonna understand Korean food.

12:19.029 --> 12:22.616
Because it's so intense
and it's still gaining a following,

12:22.700 --> 12:25.953
it won't get American-bastardized as fast.

12:26.036 --> 12:31.167
Right? There won't be a distillation to,
like, the easiest version of what it is.

12:32.334 --> 12:36.213
[Chang] I look at the spread,
and this is epic.

12:36.297 --> 12:38.966
I don't have to wait for a server
being, like, "Next course."

12:39.049 --> 12:42.595
This is modern-day eating.
People can customize what they want.

12:42.678 --> 12:43.762
It's interactive.

12:43.846 --> 12:47.766
It didn't resonate with me as someone
that was a professional cook,

12:48.767 --> 12:50.186
until, like, now.

12:50.811 --> 12:52.438
I wanna open up a Korean restaurant.

12:52.521 --> 12:54.648
-You wanna open a Korean restaurant?
-I do, I do.

12:54.732 --> 12:57.026
[laughs] Cut his legs out right now.

12:57.109 --> 12:59.236
-There's no authenticity.
-I know.

12:59.862 --> 13:02.072
-Like I'm a Korean Vanilla Ice?
-[laughs]

13:02.156 --> 13:03.991
-[Choe] You are a Korean Vanilla Ice.
-Yeah, I am.

13:04.074 --> 13:06.160
I take Korean self-loathing
to another level.

13:06.243 --> 13:07.620
Korean Vanilla Ice, though?

13:08.245 --> 13:11.499
Just do the rest of the show in Korean.
Let's hear how good your Korean is.

13:11.582 --> 13:13.876
No. I'm like a Korean
that was adopted by white parents,

13:13.959 --> 13:15.836
that has an Asian woman fetish.

13:15.920 --> 13:17.505
[all laughing]

13:22.176 --> 13:25.596
[Chang] Places and locations
that are sort of cut off from the world,

13:25.679 --> 13:28.933
you can actually create something
that's never been done before,

13:29.016 --> 13:32.061
because you're not really
copying anyone else.

13:39.401 --> 13:42.905
[Rene Redzepi] Barbecuing is not just
big chunks of meat cooking for hours,

13:42.988 --> 13:44.657
tasting a lot like smoke.

13:45.449 --> 13:47.535
It can also be very gentle cooking.

13:48.536 --> 13:52.831
Cooking on fire has become the only way
that we really cook,

13:52.915 --> 13:56.502
like, big item things,
like the bone marrows here.

13:56.585 --> 13:59.213
These are some of the items
that we use to flavor.

13:59.296 --> 14:01.590
You have stuff like blackcurrant wood.

14:02.508 --> 14:03.592
Chew on this end.

14:05.553 --> 14:06.428
Yes.

14:07.137 --> 14:09.098
There's so much flavor in this wood.

14:09.181 --> 14:11.225
It actually tastes
like blackcurrant leaves.

14:12.851 --> 14:15.980
So when you barbecue with this,
this flavor actually

14:16.605 --> 14:19.066
sort of enters the meat.

14:21.318 --> 14:23.863
This is the spruce wood. Take this one.

14:24.864 --> 14:25.739
Mmm!

14:25.823 --> 14:27.449
-Can you taste the grapefruit?
-Yeah.

14:27.533 --> 14:28.909
It's incredible.

14:28.993 --> 14:31.370
From a Christmas tree,
you can have grapefruit flavor.

14:32.705 --> 14:34.582
-Why don't we cook the leaves?
-Okay.

14:35.165 --> 14:37.710
And then it's just gonna get
this gentle smoke.

14:37.793 --> 14:40.629
Enough so that it cooks
and kind of crisps up a little bit.

14:40.713 --> 14:42.131
This is also barbecuing.

14:43.132 --> 14:45.926
[Chang] You know, having learned
over a French oven,

14:46.010 --> 14:50.222
making sure your cuisson is perfect on it,
is it harder to cook it over open flame?

14:50.306 --> 14:51.640
Of course.

14:51.724 --> 14:53.058
We've grown up in this period

14:53.142 --> 14:57.521
where the technique and the water baths
and everything,

14:57.605 --> 15:00.399
and we sort of found
our way back into this.

15:00.482 --> 15:05.112
But that level of attention
that you need to have when you cook here

15:05.195 --> 15:06.864
actually makes for a better result.

15:06.947 --> 15:07.990
Let's taste some.

15:11.118 --> 15:12.953
-Now they're changed completely.
-Yeah.

15:13.037 --> 15:16.874
Ultimately, the cooking
happens in your eyes,

15:16.957 --> 15:20.669
when you smell,
on the tip of your fingers.

15:20.753 --> 15:22.755
That's when real good cooking happens.

15:22.838 --> 15:26.634
When you are able to put
all those sensibilities into the moment.

15:27.384 --> 15:29.261
You ever get a customer from Texas?

15:29.345 --> 15:30.721
Big old guy with a cowboy hat,

15:30.804 --> 15:32.681
and you're telling him,
"This is barbecued vegetables."

15:32.765 --> 15:35.809
We had one who said, "Your portions
sure are small here." [laughs]

15:35.893 --> 15:37.478
[Chang] They're gonna be like,
"This ain't barbecue."

15:37.561 --> 15:39.813
How do you say it is?
Or does it even matter to you?

15:39.897 --> 15:41.148
No, I don't care.

15:42.983 --> 15:45.778
-I don't care, I mean...
-That is so fucking good.

15:46.737 --> 15:51.283
[Rene] Barbecue to me just represents
cooking something in embers

15:51.367 --> 15:52.910
and flaming with smoke.

15:52.993 --> 15:55.120
So, to me, this is as much barbecue,

15:55.204 --> 15:58.791
even though it's Brussels sprout
in the late winter season,

15:58.874 --> 16:04.380
as that big slab of meat that, in Texas,
you'd consider to be barbecue.

16:04.463 --> 16:05.631
In fact, I like this better.

16:10.010 --> 16:11.762
[indistinct chatter]

16:16.642 --> 16:19.979
[Bringle] People get caught up in pits
and people get caught up in fuels.

16:20.062 --> 16:22.398
They really get passionate about it.

16:22.481 --> 16:27.111
I'm passionate about telling people,
"Don't tell me how to cook my shit, okay?"

16:27.194 --> 16:28.862
