getting the meat on, firing up.

32:16.476 --> 32:19.270
So, between 3:00 and 4:00
is about my slackish time.

32:19.354 --> 32:20.980
That's when you're slacking?

32:21.064 --> 32:22.482
Between 3:00 and 4:00 in the morning?

32:22.565 --> 32:24.108
-In the morning. Mmm-hmm.
-[chuckles]

32:24.692 --> 32:26.986
[Meehan] How often were
women running the pit?

32:27.070 --> 32:28.488
Was that a commonplace thing?

32:28.571 --> 32:33.534
Oh, no. I know of very few ladies
that are pitmasters.

32:33.618 --> 32:37.747
Growing up, it was just the men
back there at the pit.

32:39.415 --> 32:40.875
[Meehan] What is the history

32:40.959 --> 32:43.836
of having this food ready at eight o'clock
in the morning?

32:43.920 --> 32:45.797
Is it from people coming
off of night shifts or--

32:45.880 --> 32:49.300
It wasn't eight o'clock
until the recognition.

32:50.468 --> 32:54.138
Texas Monthly and The New Yorker
came out with great articles.

32:54.222 --> 32:56.224
[Meehan] And then it just snowballs
from there.

32:56.307 --> 33:00.895
[Bexley] Now it's normally 40-something
people at eight o'clock.

33:00.979 --> 33:03.648
[Tootsie] The owner of Texas Monthly came

33:03.731 --> 33:07.402
and told us that we
were number one in Texas.

33:07.485 --> 33:12.323
And all Kerry and I could do
was hold each other and cry. [chuckling]

33:12.407 --> 33:18.121
We never expected anything like that
to happen from old country girl's cooking.

33:21.040 --> 33:22.375
[Meehan] These are local places

33:22.458 --> 33:26.170
where everyday people come and eat lunch
and dinner and feed their families.

33:26.254 --> 33:29.549
And that is the core of what barbecue is.

33:30.675 --> 33:33.511
It's not even a regional business.
It's a local business.

33:34.637 --> 33:37.932
I know in North Carolina
or up in the eastern states,

33:38.016 --> 33:39.976
they have the pulled pork.

33:40.059 --> 33:45.148
For me, here in Lee County in Texas,
I want a nice pretty steak.

33:45.231 --> 33:47.525
I don't want it pulled all apart.

33:48.359 --> 33:50.236
But that's just my personal feeling.

33:52.697 --> 33:54.699
-Thank you. Enjoyed it.
-Thank you.

33:54.782 --> 33:57.368
-Everything was lovely. I'll be back.
-[Tootsie laughing] Okay.

33:57.452 --> 33:58.536
Thank you.

34:00.079 --> 34:03.082
[Tootsie] It's quite an honor.
Uh, I appreciate it.

34:03.166 --> 34:04.959
[clicks tongue] Uh...

34:06.252 --> 34:08.920
A lot of people out there love me,
and I love them.

34:16.262 --> 34:20.016
[Meehan] Barbecue especially is bringing
people together around the table to eat,

34:20.099 --> 34:22.935
and that's where the whole idea
of regionalism goes out,

34:23.018 --> 34:24.896
because there's a generosity

34:24.978 --> 34:27.815
in the fact that you got up
at four o'clock this morning

34:27.899 --> 34:29.650
and drove down here and started a fire
and made us ribs

34:29.734 --> 34:32.445
-and cooked them in your way... and slept.
-[Lang] I slept here.

34:32.527 --> 34:34.489
-I would sleep here, too.
-[laughing]

34:34.572 --> 34:37.784
But going through all of that
and bringing this and serving us

34:37.867 --> 34:42.955
and that experience is the joy of food.

34:43.039 --> 34:46.292
And I think that's where all
of the partisan bickering falls apart.

34:46.375 --> 34:47.376
[Lang] I agree with that.

34:55.426 --> 34:57.470
[Chang] When I was studying
religion in college,

34:57.553 --> 34:59.764
studying a certain kind of Buddhism,

34:59.847 --> 35:03.101
and, uh, the Dalai Lama
basically said, like,

35:03.184 --> 35:07.271
"Hey, if, uh, if science proves
without a shadow of a doubt

35:07.355 --> 35:09.649
that reincarnation isn't possible,

35:09.732 --> 35:11.317
then we would adopt that."

35:12.193 --> 35:14.529
And I was like, "That's fucking crazy."

35:14.612 --> 35:18.533
It's a whole tenet of... [laughing]
for the most part, of Buddhism.

35:18.616 --> 35:21.702
And he's like, "Hey, we'll move on.
We'll accept that."

35:23.746 --> 35:25.832
I think you just have to be
open to things,

35:25.915 --> 35:28.793
because you never know
who's carrying the keys to your castle.

35:30.962 --> 35:32.880
That, to me,
is the fucking most exciting thing,

35:32.964 --> 35:37.260
is when you have this revelation, and
you're like, "Oh, I'm a fucking idiot."

35:37.343 --> 35:38.427
Right?

35:38.511 --> 35:40.680
I think you gotta be open to that.

35:43.808 --> 35:44.642
Hi.

35:46.894 --> 35:48.354
-[Kodama] Konnichiwa.
-Hi. Konnichiwa.

35:49.313 --> 35:51.023
[grunts] Can I...

35:53.901 --> 35:54.819
Hi. [speaks Japanese]

35:54.902 --> 35:56.362
[in English] Really, this is barbecue

35:56.445 --> 36:00.324
in a way that I think most people
outside of Japan don't know.

36:01.200 --> 36:04.328
Can you tell me what's so special
about this charcoal?

36:04.412 --> 36:06.539
[Kodama in Japanese]
This is Japanese binchoutan charcoal.

36:06.622 --> 36:08.749
It's really, really hard.

36:08.833 --> 36:11.711
Dealing with this
is like dealing with a living thing.

36:13.462 --> 36:16.465
The fragrance envelops
the yakitori like this.

36:16.549 --> 36:23.139
Completely different
from regular charcoal.

36:23.222 --> 36:29.312
That's the very life of the fragrance
of the binchoutan charcoal.

36:29.395 --> 36:30.396
[Chang in English]
I don't think people understand

36:30.479 --> 36:35.151
that this is not just your normal charcoal
that you use in your backyard in a grill.

36:35.234 --> 36:38.738
This is extraordinarily expensive,
extraordinarily difficult to make

36:38.821 --> 36:40.239
and really hard to buy.

36:40.323 --> 36:43.367
[in Japanese] It's only because of this
binchoutan charcoal and the ash

36:43.451 --> 36:45.411
that I'm able to cook this yakitori.

36:45.494 --> 36:48.998
[in English] Can you tell me about
the chicken and the produce that you use?

36:49.582 --> 36:53.169
[in Japanese] The bird that I use
is from where I was born, Niigata.

36:53.252 --> 36:55.546
I use Niigata bird.

36:55.630 --> 37:00.676
So I use bird from Niigata
and Niigata salt from the sea.

37:00.760 --> 37:05.223
The flame goes down bit by bit,
then the oil from the yakitori falls

37:05.306 --> 37:07.725
as it's been cooked.

37:08.851 --> 37:11.479
The oil from the bird falls down,

37:11.562 --> 37:18.194
and it's the smoke
that comes up and envelops it,

37:18.277 --> 37:19.946
cooking it that way.

37:20.029 --> 37:22.281
[in English] So, basically the fat,
when it hits the charcoal,

37:22.365 --> 37:26.327
when it smokes and flares up,
that's what gives the tori the flavor.

37:27.912 --> 37:29.580
I hate TV shows that say,

37:29.664 --> 37:31.749
"Oh, I wish there was
Smell-O-Vision in here."

37:31.832 --> 37:34.627
[chuckles softly]
But it's one of those moments

37:34.710 --> 37:40.216
where the chicken fat
in combination with the charcoal,

37:40.299 --> 37:42.343
-it smells like barbecue.
-[speaks in Japanese]

37:43.511 --> 37:44.512
Chicken tail.

37:53.646 --> 37:54.689
[speaks in Japanese]

38:00.111 --> 38:01.988
[in English] Holy shit.

38:02.071 --> 38:04.907
It's so good. You know it's delicious.

38:05.950 --> 38:09.996
[chuckles] This is not just a normal
chicken wing. It's boned out.

38:15.209 --> 38:19.005
It takes a lot of time.
It's not just blindly frying it.

38:19.088 --> 38:20.423
They do the work for you,

38:20.506 --> 38:22.717
so you can just take
a lollipop bite of this.

38:27.555 --> 38:28.764
And I'd say, for myself,

38:28.848 --> 38:31.100
this is one of my favorite things
in the world to eat.

38:32.768 --> 38:35.813
And this is the liver
that's been dipped in tare?

38:40.192 --> 38:41.277
[speaks in Japanese]

38:41.360 --> 38:43.571
[Kodama] I think this is
probably the most delicious.

38:43.654 --> 38:47.700
Eight chickens to make one skewer.

38:48.659 --> 38:50.786
[Chang in English]
This is the best yakitori I've ever had.

38:51.912 --> 38:55.541
I don't give a shit there's a camera crew
right now. I feel very lucky.

38:58.085 --> 39:01.630
[Kodama in Japanese] That's right.
The aroma's really there.

39:01.714 --> 39:04.800
Infusing that aroma is my job.

39:08.512 --> 39:09.930
[Chang in English] Hold on.

39:14.685 --> 39:16.520
Chef, I have to give you a hug.

39:16.604 --> 39:18.230
[laughing]

39:21.192 --> 39:24.820
It's... [stutters] it's unbelievably good.

39:25.863 --> 39:28.824
-Thank you. [chuckles]
-[speaks in Japanese]

39:28.908 --> 39:31.577
[in English] You guys know it.
This is not normal yakitori.

39:31.660 --> 39:32.953
This is unbelievable.

39:35.122 --> 39:38.918
He's a master. Master.

39:43.381 --> 39:44.382
Thank you.

39:50.679 --> 39:51.680
That's the...

39:52.973 --> 39:57.603
I mean, without being totally cliché
and redundant, that's as good as it gets.

39:57.686 --> 39:58.687
And...

39:59.688 --> 40:03.025
I have a hard time understanding
that he's not, like...

40:03.109 --> 40:05.611
In my mind, it's, like, world-class meal.

40:06.695 --> 40:07.780
It really is.

40:07.863 --> 40:09.907
Yes, he's very famous, but it's like...

40:09.990 --> 40:13.077
There should be a fuckin' 300-person queue
out here right now.

40:13.160 --> 40:17.248
The fact is this. You guys are out here.
I'm gonna go back inside.

40:17.331 --> 40:20.709
[stammers] This is the best fucking, uh...

40:21.877 --> 40:26.298
The best compliment I can give is,
while eating it, I'm thinking,

40:26.382 --> 40:29.301
"When can I schedule
to eat here again this week?"

40:29.385 --> 40:30.636
[chuckles]

40:32.888 --> 40:37.143
Everything you do when you take
from other cultures or other ideas,

40:37.226 --> 40:41.647
you have to internalize it
and you have to almost rationalize that,

40:41.730 --> 40:43.524
"This is how I would have done it."

40:43.607 --> 40:46.861
Or, "If this was my idea,
this is what I would've done."

40:48.696 --> 40:52.158
And it's using that as a platform
to do something better.

40:52.241 --> 40:56.454
Sometimes, that "better"
will make it worse. Right?

40:56.537 --> 40:59.707
I'm prone to do that all the time.

41:05.337 --> 41:06.672
[Chang] Playing with fire is fun.

41:08.382 --> 41:13.387
That's essentially all barbecue is to me.
It's fucking grown men playing with fire.

41:13.471 --> 41:15.431
-[Choe] Should I not open this?
-[Lang] Yeah, go ahead.

41:17.725 --> 41:19.435
Oh, my God, dude.

41:21.020 --> 41:22.897
-It tastes like kalbi, though, right?
-[Lang] Yeah.

41:22.980 --> 41:25.024
But that's not ready right now?

41:25.107 --> 41:27.109
-[Chang] Almost. Almost.
-Yeah.

41:27.193 --> 41:29.278
I don't ask you when
your fuckin' paintings are ready.

41:29.361 --> 41:30.571
-Yeah, you do.
-I do, though.

41:30.654 --> 41:32.364
-You ask me all the time.
-You're right.

41:32.448 --> 41:34.116
[laughing]

41:34.200 --> 41:36.035
Choe, why are you wearing that?

41:36.118 --> 41:37.828
I got paint all over my suit.

41:39.079 --> 41:42.208
So I have a jumpsuit with my suit on it.

41:43.042 --> 41:46.295
[Lang] I mean, this end is looking nice,
but this is where you slice from,

41:46.378 --> 41:47.630
and it's not ready.

41:47.713 --> 41:50.716
This little trick
is wrap it in plastic individually

41:50.799 --> 41:52.259
and then put it in the towel.

41:52.343 --> 41:53.719
All right, so let's do that now.

41:53.802 --> 41:56.430
-I'll get the platter, anyway.
-[Lang] Okay. Yeah.

41:56.514 --> 41:57.765
'Cause it'll hold it in.

42:00.601 --> 42:03.354
[Chang] "Make it fucking happen."
That's the name of the game.

42:03.437 --> 42:04.730
You wanna help us pack this meat?

42:04.813 --> 42:06.440
[all laughing]

42:07.525 --> 42:08.776
What's going on here?

42:10.194 --> 42:11.987
Um, it smells like lighter fluid.

42:12.071 --> 42:15.658
The whole, uh, place
is gonna go up like a powder keg.

42:16.242 --> 42:17.159
[Chang] Making kalbi.

42:17.243 --> 42:20.663
It's basically a soy,
pear-marinated short rib

42:20.746 --> 42:22.957
that people eat in Korean
barbecue all the time.

42:23.040 --> 42:24.875
But I've never seen it cooked this way.

42:24.959 --> 42:26.502
People don't wanna mess with Korean food,

42:26.585 --> 42:29.004
and people don't wanna mess
with American barbecue.

42:29.088 --> 42:30.881
-Until today.
-Until today.

42:32.675 --> 42:34.093
[Choe] So this is the new style.

42:34.176 --> 42:35.844
And, what,
my mom's gonna do the traditional?

42:35.928 --> 42:38.514
[Chang] Yeah, your mom's gonna do
traditional Korean barbecue.

42:38.597 --> 42:43.102
-[Choe] Ooh.
-Smells delicious. Very well. [chuckles]

42:43.185 --> 42:45.771
-Finally here.
-[speaks Korean]

42:45.854 --> 42:48.107
[Yeun in English]
Oh, is this a taste-test comparison?

42:48.190 --> 42:49.692
[Choe] I didn't know
we were in a meat-off.

42:49.775 --> 42:52.486
-Is it the same marinades, or are you--
-[Chang] Yeah.

42:52.570 --> 42:54.697
That's basically Mama Chang's marinade.

42:54.780 --> 42:56.365
Just different style.

42:56.448 --> 42:58.492
Dude, you gotta touch it.
It's like meat Jell-O.

42:58.576 --> 43:02.621
-Yo, that looks bonkers.
-[Chang] I'll let the master do it.

43:03.539 --> 43:05.332
[Choe] Mom, you can have the first taste.

43:05.416 --> 43:08.085
-[Yeun] Whoa. Word.
-[Lang] You should eat this.

43:11.046 --> 43:13.007
-I love it. Mmm.
-[Choe] Do you like it?

43:13.090 --> 43:14.300
[Chang] And that's ssamjang.

43:14.383 --> 43:17.720
That's with chickpea
instead of your traditional miso.

43:18.429 --> 43:19.555
I feel like now it's healthy.

43:19.638 --> 43:21.307
-Now that it's been wrapped in leather.
-[all laugh]

43:23.684 --> 43:25.853
[Yeun]
Do you think it tastes Korean, though?

43:25.936 --> 43:27.521
[Chang] How is it not Korean?

43:27.605 --> 43:29.815
It's my mom's recipe.
It's a kalbi marinade.

43:30.691 --> 43:33.068
-I soaked it in for 48 hours.
-Yeah.

43:33.152 --> 43:35.738
-And I cooked it over charcoal.
-[Yeun] Right.

43:35.821 --> 43:37.990
[Chang] How is that not Korean barbecue?

43:38.073 --> 43:39.158
[Jae Ohk Choe] Oh.

43:41.118 --> 43:44.830
There's so many things on the table,
it's hard to keep track of.

43:44.913 --> 43:47.333
Man, we're gonna eat
till we're so unhappy.

43:47.416 --> 43:49.293
-[Jae Ohk Choe laughs]
-[Kimmel] Wow.

43:49.376 --> 43:52.046
-Wow. I like that. That's great.
-[Jae Ohk Choe] Yes.

43:52.129 --> 43:55.507
Koreans must spend a lot of time
washing dishes.

43:55.591 --> 43:56.717
-[laughter]
-[Jae Ohk Choe] I have a dishwasher.

43:56.800 --> 43:58.135
-[Chang] Cheers, guys.
-[all] Cheers.

43:58.218 --> 44:00.346
-Thank you so much.
-[Chang] To barbecue of new and old.

44:00.429 --> 44:02.056
[Jae Ohk Choe] Thank God for everything.

44:02.139 --> 44:03.724
Thank God for everything.

44:03.807 --> 44:05.517
To the white guys. Thank you.

44:05.601 --> 44:06.602
[laughing]

44:06.685 --> 44:10.147
